Former Pitt
scientist wins
naﬁonal
physics award

The American Physical Society has
given an award to a former Pitt physi-
cist who has tackled some of the same
problems as Albert Einstein.

Dr. Luis Lehner received the
Nicholas Metropolis Award for 1999 in
recognition of work he did to develop a
method to model gravitational radia-
tion. His work makes it possible to
solve one of Einstein’s equations deal-
ing with black holes in space. The APS
said Lehner’s work “significantly
advances” progress in this area.

The work done by Lehner, in con-
junction with a team lead by Pitt facul-
ty member Jeffrey Winicour, is consid-
ered a “grand challenge” of physics and

, is a part of the completion of the laser

interferometric gravity observatories
that the National Science Foundation is
building in the states of Washington
and Louisiana.

Lehner said he was surprised to
receive the award because he works in
the fields of astrophysics and relativity.
The work he was awarded for deals
with ﬂuid dynamics.

His time at Pitt was beneficial,
Lehner said, because he matured as a
physicist and as an individual, due
largely to guidance from'Winicour, his

A adviser, and Dr. Roberto Gomez, anoth-

er faculty member.

Lehner, a native of Argentina, cur-
rently holds a postdoctoral position at
the University of Texas.

The Nicholas Metropolis award is
named after one of the mathematicians
involved in first using digital comput-
ers to solve complex problems in
physics.

——Frank Holland, Staff Writer

