EDITORIAL

Colt’s smart gun addresses safety
concerns, but it's still way off

For all those worried about gun
safety, Colt has taken the initiative
to release a “smart gun” —— a
ﬁrearm that can only be ﬁred by its
owner. .

The smart gun can only be ﬁred
if the shooter wears a special
bracelet with a microchip that
matches the radio frequency of the
chip on the gun. So if you’re hold-
ing the gun, and you don’t have its
matching bracelet, the hammer will
not snap down.

Colt’s new gun, which should
improve safety and prevent people
trying to defend themselves from
being shot with their own guns, wiH
also redeﬁne the gun debate. Since
it addresses issues such as child
safety and self-defense, it has
attracted praise from several sectors
of the gun-control lobby.

“The only people who oppose
or question the usefulness of devel-
oping smart guns are the extremists
at both ends of the gtm-control
debate,” said Naomi Paiss, the com-
munications director for Handgun
Control, a gun-control lobbyist
group. ‘ '

In a declining gun market, Colt
has shown some initiative in bring-
ing out the smart gun, aimed at con-
sumers’ worried about their guns
falling into the wrong hands -
their children’s or a crirninal’s.

Though Colt is not the only gun
manufacturer developing a comput-
erized gun designed to be ﬁred only
by its owner, its is the closest to
production.

Deﬁnitely a step in the right
direction, the new gun still does not
solve all the problems. VV1th the
bracelet, there is the issue of keep-
ing it separate from the gun, keep-
ing it secure or having to wear it all
the time. Not that different from the
concern over where the keys to the
gun safe should be kept.

If a burglar breaks into the
house, and you’re not wearing the
bracelet, he could storm into your
bedroom and kill you in the time
you take-to ﬁnd it, fumble for it and
slip it onto your wrist. In the process
of developing a safe gun, it seems
Colt may have forsaken conve-
nience in times when you really
need a gun loaded and ready to
shoot.

But if kids are a concern and
you’re wonied about your gun
being stolen and used by criminals
to commit crimes, Colt’s smart gun
is a good idea. Also, there is less
chance for police officers’ weapons
to be used against them.

As technology improves, guns
will undoubtedly be a lot safer.
Until then, the smart gun will suf-
ﬁce.

  

    

