STEP valuable
introduction to college

As a former student in the Summer
Transitional Education Program, I felt the
Oct. 20 Pitt News staff editorial was disturb-
ing. I had conre to Pitt through STEP
because of reasons beyond my control.
STEP gave me the opportunity to prove that
I can handle the college workload and live a
college life. STEP is not all about grades and
classes; STEP is about maturing and leam—
ing to live on your own and to be responsi-
ble for your own actions. .

STEP gave me the opportunity to learn
those lessons before the rest of the freshman
class arrived in the fall. The students I knew
who did not attend STEP seemed unable to
handle the load and were overwhelmed with
the whole college atmosphere. Though the
classes were not as challenging as my cur-
rent classes, the challenge of STEP was
learning how to live and learn in college.

When I told many people that I had
attended STEP, many wished they could
have, too. When they arrived in the fall,
walking around lost and confused and won-
dering what was going on, I was telling
them where to go and what to do.

IamgladPittistryingtoimproveits
image, but blaming the lack of academic
perfonnance on STEP is ludicrous, inappro-
priate and insulting. Obviously, the Editorial
Board did not attend STEP and did not wit-
ness the program’s positive contributions to
this school.

Although we were affectionately
labeled “Stupid Teens Entering Pitt,” we
have contributed positively to this university

and have learned valuable lessons that will ,

enable us to be one STEP ahead.

Peter Bell
Class of 2001

